    "markdown": "---\nformat:\n  html:\n    css: styles.css\n    embed-resources: TRUE\n    code-fold: true\n    page-layout: full\n    fig_caption: yes\n---\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n:::\n\n\n::: narrow-section\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"grid-container\" style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); justify-items: center;\">\n<div id=\"highlight-text\">824</div>\n<div id=\"highlight-text\">1,135</div>\n<div style=\"display: block; &#10;              color: #ff6400; &#10;              font-size: 1.25em; &#10;              font-family: Graphik; &#10;              font-weight: bold; &#10;              text-align: center;\">Extremely High<br>Indeterminacy</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">Currently Eligible for<br>Parole but in Prison</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">Eligible for Parole in<br>the next 1-5 years</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">\n<span class=\"tippy html-widget html-fill-item-overflow-hidden html-fill-item\" height=\"338px\" id=\"htmlwidget-f6a1a3b2e619d3917cd6\" width=\"100%\"></span>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-f6a1a3b2e619d3917cd6\">{\"x\":{\"opts\":{\"placement\":\"bottom\",\"flip\":true,\"theme\":\"light\",\"content\":\"To compare the degrees of indeterminacy, or unpredictability\\n   of time served, of prison-sentencing systems of different jurisdictions,\\n   we use a qualitative ranking framework based on the Robina Institute's\\n   Prison-release Discretion And Prison Population Size Report.<br><br><b>Extremely High Indeterminacy<\\/b>: >80-100 percent indeterminacy (first prospect of release at 0-19.99 percent of judicial maximum).\"},\"text\":\"<span aria-label=\\\"To compare the degrees of indeterminacy, or unpredictability\\n   of time served, of prison-sentencing systems of different jurisdictions,\\n   we use a qualitative ranking framework based on the Robina Institute's\\n   Prison-release Discretion And Prison Population Size Report.<br><br><b>Extremely High Indeterminacy<\\/b>: >80-100 percent indeterminacy (first prospect of release at 0-19.99 percent of judicial maximum).\\\" tabindex=\\\"0\\\" role=\\\"button\\\">Prison Sentencing<br>System&#9432;<\\/span>\"},\"evals\":[],\"jsHooks\":[]}</script>\n</div>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n\n<br>\n\n\n\n::: panel-tabset \n\n## Parole Eligibility\n\n<center>\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">How is Parole Release Eligibility Determined?</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">Hawaii has a largely indeterminate sentencing system in which the court sets only the maximum period of incarceration. Thus, when a person has been sentenced to an indeterminate or extended term of imprisonment, the Hawaii Paroling Authority must hold a hearing no later than six months after commitment to incarceration to determine the minimum term of imprisonment and issue a “tentative parole date” or “TPD.” This means that there is often a “minimum” hearing and a “parole release hearing” that are separate. The TPD can later be reduced at the discretion of the Authority with sixty days’ notice to the prosecuting attorney. Note that the Authority can only hear felony cases; misdemeanants are given determinate sentences fixed by the court. The parole guidelines determine the earliest potential release date.  Unless good cause is shown, offenders who have been assessed as low-risk must be granted parole at the earliest guideline release date.</div>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">People who are Eligible for Parole</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"bar-chart\">\n<div id=\"htmlwidget-b544a430352341456cf6\" style=\"width:100%;height:454px;\" class=\"highchart html-widget \"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-b544a430352341456cf6\">{\"x\":{\"hc_opts\":{\"chart\":{\"reflow\":true,\"width\":500,\"height\":350},\"title\":{\"text\":\"People who are Parole Eligible but Still in Prison 